"I just asked that question to ChatGPT.         Short answer: no — I wasn’t directly “fed” or trained on specific books by Neil deGrasse Tyson (or any single author in a targeted way).
Here’s how it actually works:
How my training works
I was trained on a mixture of data, including:
Publicly available text (websites, articles, educational content)
Licensed data
Data created by human trainers
That mix includes general knowledge about science, astronomy, and physics, which people like Neil deGrasse Tyson also talk about—but not his books specifically as a defined dataset.
So why I sound similar sometimes
If I explain something like black holes or the universe in a way that feels familiar, it’s because:
I learned common scientific explanations used across many sources
Popular communicators like Tyson, Carl Sagan, etc., helped shape how science is explained publicly
Important distinction
❌ Not trained on: “Here are Tyson’s books—learn them”
✅ Trained on: Broad patterns of language and knowledge, some of which overlap with ideas he explains
If you want, I can explain things in his style (more cosmic, storytelling, philosophical), or compare how he explains concepts vs. others.",AI,0
