"What's happening overseas isn’t just “their” problem — it affects every one of us. When violence erupts anywhere, humanity feels it everywhere.

War doesn’t create winners.  
It creates broken families, lost futures, and pain that echoes for generations.  
It takes from people who never asked to be part of the fight.

As leaders, as neighbors, as human beings, we should expect more from those who hold power. We should expect empathy. Wisdom. Restraint. A commitment to peace before pride. Decisions that protect people, not egos.

Because the truth is simple:  
When leaders choose violence, the world loses something sacred.

I believe we can do better.  
I believe we must do better.

Let’s be the voices that remind the world what matters — compassion, dialogue, understanding, and the courage to choose peace even when it’s difficult. Let’s stand for a future where conflicts are solved through conversation, not destruction. Where humanity comes before ambition.

This moment hurts.  
But it also calls us to rise with clarity and purpose.

Let’s be the generation that refuses to accept war as the answer.",Economy,0
"If Congress doesn’t step in and stop this escalation, the reality of war may one day reach our own soil — and when it does, the United States will finally understand what so many families around the world already know. War is not a headline. It is not a political talking point. It is devastation, fear, and loss.

