As of late February 2026, including his 2026 State of the Union address, here is a summary of the recorded misinformation:
2026 State of the Union Address: In his 108-minute address on February 24, 2026, a review of 63 verifiable claims found that 22 were factually false or significantly exaggerated, while 27 were partially true or misleading.
Key Areas of Misinformation (2025-2026):
Economy: Trump has claimed his policies created an economic boom, but data indicates job growth slowed in 2025, and inflation did not stop as he asserted. He inaccurately claimed that a 2025 domestic policy bill was the ""most popular bill ever signed"".
Immigration: He has frequently repeated the false claim that other countries emptied their prisons and mental institutions, sending inmates to the U.S. border.
2020 Election: He has continued to repeat the falsehood that the 2020 election was stolen.
""Bottomless"" Claims: Similar to his first term, Trump has continued to repeat false claims dozens of times, such as regarding the ""no tax on Social Security"" pledge, which experts note is not fully accurate.
Context: Following a record of over 30,000 documented untruths during his first term (2017-2021), fact-checkers have noted that the pace of false claims in his second term has remained high. 
