"Raising interest rates is a key monetary policy tool used to control inflation. When central banks increase interest rates, borrowing becomes more expensive for businesses and individuals. This discourages excessive spending and investment, leading to reduced demand for goods and services. As demand slows, businesses are less likely to raise prices, helping to curb inflation. Higher interest rates also attract foreign investment, strengthening the currency and lowering the cost of imported goods. Additionally, consumers save more due to higher returns on savings, further reducing money circulation. By cooling down excessive economic activity, higher interest rates help stabilize inflation levels.",Economy,0
