"People don't understand that inflation is a rate of increase, it has nothing to do with making things cheaper. Once it happens, values generally never go back down, you just adjust for the differences if you're a decent country. Imagine if in Japan people were still being paid the same as they were decades ago before the massive spending on infrastructure and other inflation spiking events/policies happened. They get paid 20 yen (today that's about 13 US cents) and a bottle of soda would be 200 yen (today, roughly 1.30 or so US cents... which isn't bad considering they're nearly 3 dollars in the US... almost like we're getting gouged).

That's more or less what's happening the US. costs of goods increase over time, even with a small rate of 1 to 2% on average, but pay stagnated for the majority of people while the top wealthiest has been borderline exponentially increasing. People cry ""late stage capitalism"", but the reason cost on luxury goods like iPhones, Graphics cards, etc. has sky rocketed is less to do with actual cost and more to with the fact people line up around city blocks to buy them even when they double the price. The fools during the pandemic that bought nvidia GPUs that should have been around 600 bucks (and were MSRP) for 1000-2000 dollars faster than scalpers could list them are what drove prices up more than anything else.

