"Honestly I would only buy new for the lowest option and just upgrade to the latest higher performance when I need to. It would be far cheaper and any bug or problems and whatever improvements have generally been done. As long as there is no exploding or chip defects going on then that should not be a concern for the used market. Given CPUs don't really need to keep up compared to GPUs with games lately, its fine enough. Even if its one cycle, if the ram can swap over then its not that bad a deal especially that any current generation of CPUs need DDR5, you will need to buy ram if you upgrade from a older rig unless you are 12th gen Intel upgrading and don't want to use 14th gen. It is a mine field of getting used 14th gen and not fully knowing if it was a damaged one or not. 

Given that its more than a CPU socket with MB upgrades, given over just a decade, M.2 stots have become a normal inclusion if not multiple of them. PCI-e upgrades went from PCI-e 3.0 to 5.0, The number of USB ports have increased heavily. The speed of ports and types of ports have increased dramaticly. Wifi and Bluetooth upgrades have dramatically increased. Number of on board fan ports, RGB port USB ports have increased. Honestly currently I don't expect much real noticeable change in MBs unlike from a decade ago or longer since many of the improvement were QOL which have kinda been taken care of. 

I bet a lot of people are on the 10th/11th gen intel and the barely hanging on 5000 series (you know very well that the 5000X3D is a last ditch effort, a good effort that paid off for gamers) because you know many of them are using MBs that is older than the 5000 series. There has been a lot for the MBs in changes that are really worth doing and prices for MBs can only go down so far before the lack of availability of MBs start giving sellers the ""this is now rare and worth so much more""",Tech,0
